Angelia Lau

Data Scientist & Software Engineer

PORTFOLIO

311 COVID-19 Comparison

As a follow up to my previous work on 311, I visualized the differences in NYC's 311 complaint volumes across time, before and during the COVID-19 pandemic.

311 Cross City Comparison

As a Civic Analytics Fellow, I advanced an algorithmic model to derive 37 standard 311 citizen complaint categories from more than 7700 unique categories, across 25 North American and Canadian Cities. Through Natural Language Processing, and by utilizing my model, I visualized differences between and within cities that implemented this public service delivery system.

Phone Usage, Paired Walking and Loitering Behaviors on NYC Times Square and Shinjuku City Sidewalks

In this project, I surveyed multiple walking tour youtube videos on NYC Times Square and Shinjuku City's Shinjuku Station areas. I derived multiple social, environmental, physical and behavioral factors pertaining to three sidewalk behaviors: pedestrians focusing on their handheld devices, pedestrians walking in pairs, and pedestrians who were waiting or loitering. Summary statistics were computed and summarized as visualizations, implemented in Python, with pandas, matplotlib and sea

Differentiating and Predicting Community Gardens based on Neighborhood Profiles in NYC

In this data-intensive project, I collaborated in a team of three to engage the question: in NYC, are community gardens exclusive to certain types of neighborhoods? Relevant data was either obtained from the open data portal or scrapped from websites, later cleaned and at times, involved spatial joins. Lastly, we employed clustering and binary classification techniques and evaluated our findings.

Raising Jersey City's Building Inspection Pass Rates

In this project, I worked with the Jersey City's Office of Construction Code Official to investigate the cause of low building inspection pass rates. Gathering insights using analytics and interviews with inspectors, I proposed an implementable and cost effective solution.

Spatial Autocorrelation in MTA Passenger Seat Choice

In this project, global and local spatial autocorrelation were leveraged upon to examine where MTA passengers choose to sit on NYC MTA trains (specifically the R-64 cars that run on the A/C/F/R). The research found strong negative correlations in seat choice, suggesting a general preference for privacy and social conservative behaviors.

Geographical Factors Influencing Pedestrian Behaviors At Jay St/MetroTech

In this project, I conducted spatial and geographical analysis on how pedestrians utilise crosswalks at the crossing between Mariot Hotel and MetroTech. Primary data collection was designed, implemented and evaluated. Urban design features and affordances were raised as possible geographical factors influencing pedestrian behaviors.

SUTD Capstone: Samsung Shooshoe

ShooShoe is an automated shoe storage, sorting and retrieval system that is envisioned for the modern Smart Home. It combines intelligent robotics, user-centric design and artificial intelligence to solve and anticipate the needs of each user. In our team of 7, and in partnership with Samsung, we designed and built this from scratch.

MIT-SUTD Global Leadership Programme (Scholar)

I spent 2 weeks on Leadership training and 8 weeks designing and building a working electric boat at the International Design Centre (IDC) of MIT. I completed a skills bootcamp involving 3D modelling (Solidworks, AutoCad), 3D printing, electrical skills, carpentry skills, using workshop machines and CNC machines. With a team of 5, I brainstormed, sketched, visualised, iterated on designs for this electric boat. During this summer, I also attended a Coldplay concert and skydived for the first time!

ABOUT

I'm a graduate student at New York University's Center for Urban Science and Progress (NYU CUSP), and a Civic Analytics Fellow at NYU Marron Institute of Urban Management.

I am passionate about data science applications in the public interest and urban domains. I love exploratory data analysis and data storytelling through visualizations.
